snippet.textDisplay: Wow! Dylan, this song defies description, as I fell out of the silence that surrounded me, to listen to such caring mesmerizing lyrics, with a haunting, yet soothing violin, easy flowing piano, all given pure expressive from a soulful calming voice. It's this feeling I have, that Bob Dylan's chosen that it's time to take up the gauntlet, as he's challenged himself, to do something that is difficult, but necessary, though he sings this mournful tune very tenderly, seeming so effortless. I'm amazed, as in our time, now, Dylan's shed light from our past, rekindled fine memories that there is good in being ‘human’,-when-‘kind’. This is epic, highly inspiring, for us to carry on, see through the darkness, knowing there's hope and truth that reigns over sadness and injustice. Wonderful!

snippet.textDisplay:
My take - Bob wants to do something- something to help all who care about his music, anyone who’s been moved by his God-given genius. His fans and followers. He tells us that in his message.
He clearly still is affected by the events of November 1963. Everything changed after that. The world would never be the same. But the world, and we, went on.
I was very young but I still feel the effects as well - it’s a part of me somehow.
For him, it’s all about music and popular culture. He makes that clear as he references famous people and things. These are the some examples , seemingly random and certainly diverse, things that bring enrichment to our mundane lives. The Arts. The essence of the world he lives in and how he reaches all that care about what he contributes.
In the end, this is a way the is he trying to
cope with the tragedy (and wants to encourage us) that we must and will get through.
It’s the story of life. Of the pain and triumph that is the human experience.
I found it, at the very least and in his own word , interesting.

snippet.textDisplay: A lot of people may not get this but Dylan actually name checks three well-known and likely participants of the foul deed in the lyrics. In one early section he references “sliding down the banister” (referencing the slippery FBI informant Guy Bannister), mentions the “ferry crossing the Mersey” (song check but also an allusion to the very culpable CIA asset David Ferry who drove from Houston to Dallas the night before Nov. 22nd and was himself murdered just before Garrison’s trial in ‘67) and finally the infamous and conspicuous “three bums” found right after the scene and inexplicably let go by Dallas police, never to be heard from again. Dylan’s definitely read the seminal “JFK and the Unspeakable.”
